    "wikipediaUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Church-Field",
    "extract": "The Church-Field was an early American electric car manufactured in Sibley, Michigan, by the Church-Field Motor Company from 1912–1913. The Church-Field had an underslung chassis, and used a two-speed transmission. With a choice of ten electrical selector positions, it gave the vehicle a total choice of twenty speed ranges. Two body styles were offered - a roadster sold for $2300 and a coupe for $2800."
